<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-546-407  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 546 407.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Oct 11 1990 v35 n21 p137(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alternating voltage DVM calibrates top-end ac calibrationinstruments. (digital voltmeter)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kerridge, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Datron Instruments' 4920 digital voltmeter (DVM), $9,995, offersseveral advantages over calibration instruments that depend ontraditional thermal techniques.andP;  Convenience and portability areimportant features as well as the DVM's settling time of less than2.5 seconds to meet full accuracy specification for frequenciesover 100 Hz.andP;  Operation of the 4920 is programmable using anIEEE-488.2 interface.andP;  The 4920's accuracy positions it betweenthe National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) andtop-end ac calibration instruments.andP;  Optimal total-measurementuncertainty is plus or minus 38 ppm for inputs of 0.9 to 11V, andfor input frequencies of 40 Hz to 30 KHz, when the 4920 is used asa conventional DVM.andP;  Measurement uncertainty improves to plus orminus 28 ppm when users make a measurement at a pre-calibratedspot in the 40 Hz to 30 KHz frequency range.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Datron Instruments (product introduction).andO;Product:   Datron Instruments 4920 (Voltmeter) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     CalibrationVoltageProduct Introduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationdiagram.andO;Caption:   The 4920 can simplify re-calibrating premium ac calibrationinstruments. (diagram)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>